						<p>It's a line from Vergil, originally "yet meanwhile time flies, flies irreparably, while [we're] captivated by our love for detail", altered to "yet auctoritas flies, flies irreparably, while [you're] captivated by your expectation of banality". </p>
<p>Neither English version is exact, and a whole treatise could be written on the points of departure. In particular the meaning of auctoritas is not available to one who's not versed in classical antiquity (and a degree of any kind obtained in an English speaking country does not attest such qualification). But, for the needs of the incurious, "sovereignity" might do.</p>
						</li>

